uch as fever, cough, and skin infections. The plant's leaves and roots are traditionally used in Ayurvedic medicine, where they are believed to possess anti-inflammatory and antibacterial properties. Studies have also shown that Burragea frutescens may have antifungal and antioxidant properties. Further research is needed to fully understand the plant's medicinal potential and its effects on human health.", "taxonomy": "Burragea frutescens is classified within the family Rutaceae, commonly known as the rue or orange family of flowering plants. This family comprises over 160 genera and approximately 1,500 species, many of which are economically important for their fruit, leaves, and essential oils. As a member of Rutaceae, Burragea frutescens shares characteristics with other plants in the family, such as the presence of aromatic compounds and the production of small, fragrant flowers. The plant's classification also places it within the order Sapindales, a group of flowering plants known for their diverse range of fruit types and growth habits. Further classification of Burragea frutescens includes its placement within the tribe Citreae, a subfamily of Rutaceae that includes many citrus species.", "benefits": "Burragea frutescens, commonly known as the Indian plum, has been used in traditional medicine for its various health benefits. The plant's fruits, leaves, and bark are rich in antioxidants, which help to protect the body from oxidative stress and inflammation. The plant is also believed to have anti-diabetic, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, which may help to manage conditions such as diabetes and certain infections. In addition, the plant is said to possess anti-cancer properties, which may help to prevent the growth and spread of cancer cells. Further research is needed to confirm the effectiveness of Burragea frutescens in treating various health conditions.", "parts": "Burragea frutescens, a species of flowering plant, is known for its medicinal properties. The leaves of Burragea frutescens are used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments. The plant's root is also utilized in traditional remedies to address digestive issues and fever. In Ayurvedic medicine, Burragea frutescens is valued for its anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. The plant's extracts are used to treat a range of health conditions, from skin problems to respiratory issues.", "intro": "Burragea frutescens, also known as \"Kokum,\" is a plant species native to the Western Ghats of India, belonging to the Rutaceae family and used in traditional medicine. The health benefits of Burragea frutescens include its anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and antimicrobial properties, which have been traditionally used to treat various health issues such as fever, rheumatism, and skin conditions. The bioactive constituents of Burragea frutescens include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, particularly the alkaloid and glycoside compounds, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made with Burragea frutescens include extracts, infusions, and decoctions, often used in traditional Indian medicine, Ayurveda, to treat a range of health conditions."}